<TEXT>
a bronze sculpture at the base of a 
neonoutlined 16story office tower here honors real estate 
developer conley wolfswinkels parents without whose love and 
guidance this building never would have been possible 
not exactly western savings amp loan association and ultimately 
the us taxpayer helped too 
the nowdefunct sampl paid wolfswinkel 525 million the amount 
of his loan for the tower three years ago government regulators 
sold the building this summer for 203 million 
loss to taxpayers more than 32 million just on that building 
such dealings multipled over and over again across the country 
illustrate where the money went in the sampl fiasco 
first texas savings and loan loaned 325 million to build 
stonebridge ranch a planned community north of dallas first texas 
failed and regulators this year could muster only 61 million for 
stonebridge from a japanese investor leaving taxpayers on the hook 
for 264 million 
tales of fraud highliving and ripoffs dominate the coverage 
of the sampl crisis but analysts and regulators say only a fraction 
of the money lost estimated to run as high as 500 billion was 
stolen outright most of it was gambled away on risky real estate 
deals 
it was like staking poker players to piles of chips while 
allowing them to keep any winnings even as the government agreed 
to pay all the losses said sherman maisel former federal 
reserve board governor 
fraud accounted for about 3 percent of the total being absorbed 
by taxpayers according to consultant bert ely the bulk of the 
losses come from devalued real estate and excessive interest rates 
paid by sick sampls to attract depositors 
the crookbashing is troubling they make convenient 
scapegoats to avoid focusing attention on the failed government 
policies that caused this ely said 
weve wasted the economic resources of the 1980s on unneeded 
investments he said were already had the binge now weve 
got the hangover for it 
ely estimates the loss today at 147 billion he figures 28 
billion went down the drain in property that is worth less now than 
when it was financed or bought by a thrift 
the rest was lost in a variety of ways 
excess interest paid to attract deposits or just to keep pace 
with the highflying thrifts that offered abovemarket rates to 
provide more cash to gamble 
excess operating costs exorbitant salaries unneeded branch 
offices lavish decorations jets yachts and fancy parties ely 
said 
fixedrate mortgages made before 1983 and squeezed by higher 
interest rates 
interest paid to keep ailing thrifts alive instead of closing 
them and paying off depositors immediately 
its a massive government failure said robert litan a 
senior fellow at the brookings institution most of the money was 
lost in wild gambles the government let them do it there was no 
supervision 
some profited through the whole episode people who originally 
sold land made a bundle money was paid to contractors developers 
suppliers and construction workers in a building boom that went 
bust when regional economies nosedived 
but fraud has generated the biggest headlines even though the 
us justice department estimates criminal acts in about 30 percent 
of the failed sampls 
youve got a lot of creeps in there but criminal fraud didnt 
create the problem said doug tillet spokesman for the justice 
department we see an awful lot of stupidity and bad judgment 
thats not prosecutable 
</TEXT>
