<TEXT>
negotiators are reporting the first 
breakthrough in drafting a compromise clean air bill with a 
tentative agreement between the house and senate on the control of 
smogcausing pollution from industry 
congressional sources emphasized however that there remained 
major differences that have yet to be resolved despite mounting 
time pressures congress plans to adjourn in early october 
the sources who demanded anonymity said staff negotiators 
agreed monday on measures to be taken against industry to control 
urban smog they opted for tougher house provisions that would 
require even small businesses to install new control equipment in 
areas with severe pollution 
the staff agreement was reached with the knowledge of lawmakers 
on the housesenate conference committee although committee 
members must still formally sign off on it said one source close 
to the negotiations 
the committee has tried since june to resolve differences in 
separate clean air bills that were approved by wide margins in the 
house and senate early this year 
the agreement on socalled title i which includes the 
industrial smogcontrol provisions and general air quality goals 
for communities was considered a major step forward in the 
discussions 
this is one of the major hurdles said daniel weiss who has 
followed the clean air debates for the sierra club an 
environmental group 
the massive and complex legislation calls for steep cuts in acid 
rain tougher emission controls on automobiles requirements that 
oil companies produce cleaner fuels and controls on toxic chemical 
releases the new requirements are predicted to cost industry 25 
billion a year when all take effect at the end of the decade 
the price tag has caused industry to intensify its lobbying 
against portions of the bill in view of skyrocketing oil prices and 
the increasing prospects of a recession 
the bush administration had opposed the stronger industrial smog 
controls tentatively agreed to monday saying that if small 
companies are required to install new control equipment the 
legislation will become too expensive environmentalists argued 
that small polluters account for nearly half of the smog in many 
urban areas 
under the agreement factories and businesses that release as 
little as 25 to 50 tons of pollution annually would be required to 
comply with new controls the senate bill had exempted facilities 
that release less than 100 tons of pollution per year 
meanwhile other controversial parts of the bill remain to be 
worked out including whether to provide financial assistance to 
workers who lose their jobs because of tougher pollution controls 
some lawmakers have also suggested that parts of the bill should 
be reexamined in light of the mideast crisis and the latest oil 
shocks 
we may have to begin to reassess what is realistic said 
democratic rep mike synar of oklahoma a leading oil state he 
suggested that some pollution control requirements on the petroleum 
industry and a mandate for cleaner fuels might have to be delayed 
nevertheless the agreement monday on industrial pollution 
represents the most significant progress yet in crafting a final 
bill 
the staff agreement also includes deadlines on when communities 
must comply with federal air quality requirements both the house 
and senate versions had similar deadlines giving most cities five 
to 15 years to bring their air into compliance with federal health 
standards los angeles was given 20 years 
but the agreement goes along with a house provision that would 
continue to require the federal government to impose air pollution 
control plans if cities fail to do so the senate version would 
have ended that federal requirement 
</TEXT>
