<TEXT>
the bedouins of jordan hearing holy war in 
the wind pray to allah that a modern clash of wills will not make 
their ancient desert life vanish in the sands 
among the bedouins for centuries guided more by water and whim 
than by lines on a map any conflict threatens to restrict 
movement further threatening a way of life already in danger 
war will damage the whole world said mohammed salim 
squatting on his heels in a burlaprag tent near this city north of 
amman and the bedouin will suffer especially 
he wonders if he can go to saudi arabia or if he wants to 
under a climate of hostility over iraqs aug 2 seizure of kuwait 
he worries about market shortages in jordan 
far to the south near petra ali salim bedol watched the iraqi 
leader saddam hussein on a television set in the concrete block 
shelter given to him when bedouins were evicted from the 
2000yearold ruins now a major tourist attraction 
saddam is a great man he said but we do not want war no 
one can win if there is fighting we want only peace to take our 
goats and camels where we want and to live among arabs 
about 150000 bedouins live regularly in jordan under black 
goathair tents or in tumbledown hovels making up 5 percent of the 
total population some stay put but most pick up and roam at will 
another 9000 are nomads drifting back and forth toward saudi 
arabia whence bedouin tribes came when the hashemite royal family 
settled in jordan after world war i the family had left the hejaz 
saudi arabias arabic name 
despite the bedouins warlike reputation and their deep sense 
of honor most seem to reject saddams call to arms 
instead they follow events by radio newspapers passed from 
hand to hand or the occasional word from travelers they discuss 
the crisis endlessly around campfires at night 
they are hit hard by the crisis said rebecca salti who 
runs a save the children crafts project for bedouins in the desert 
east of amman many are afraid israel will attack and overrun 
their grazing lands 
bedouins once bolstered the political and military power base 
behind jordans king hussein camelmounted troops of the fabled 
arab legion enhanced their prestige and mystique 
but severe drought in the 1970s killed their animals and brought 
many bedouin families to the outskirts of towns army service paid 
high wages which inevitably meant changes in the old way of life 
today many families live precariously at the edge still 
fiercely loyal to the king but marginal to life in jordan 
a bedouin who would identify himself only as salam keeps his two 
wives 19 children two camels and small herd of goats in a tent 
compound on a barren hillside near zarqa 
with no income beyond what his animals produce he survives by 
the curious third world mathematics which defy all accounting if 
the crisis continues he said his delicate balance will tilt 
never mind he said for a poor man there is no fear in 
death a bedouin needs nothing we make clothes from our goats we 
have yogurt meat that is enough 
but his sons are in school and he thinks of the future they 
may be engineers or doctors by day and bedouins when they return at 
night he said he supports saddam but wants no war 
every country will be different if there is war he said 
we will not escape 
pressed for his full name he chuckled and said salam yachak 
el haya it wasnt his name in arabic it means salam loves life 
ali salim bedol is already suffering he once earned a modest 
living selling souvenirs to tourists at petra now the tourists 
are gone 
we will go to the desert if crisis comes he said there 
will always be a bedouin way 
his 17yearold son wearing a mickey mouse tshirt and 
captivated by the television looked doubtful 
