alkharj saudi arabia ap waves of grain that will 
eventually provide us soldiers with bread spring from the same 
scorching reclaimed desert the troops were sent to protect 
saudi tomatoes on the other hand have it easier they are 
pampered in airconditioned greenhouses 
agriculture experts say saudi arabias drive to food 
selfsufficiency is being pushed even harder by the persian gulf 
crisis 
saudi arabia with annual rainfall averaging 4 inches produces 
all its own wheat and most of its milk and vegetables its an 
amazing thing that they have done said one western diplomat 
the kingdom is confident it can retain its position as the 
worlds sixth largest wheat exporter despite the loss of markets in 
iraq and kuwait the two countries bought 450000 tons annually in 
all saudi arabia exports 19 million tons to 42 countries 
it wont hurt said mohammed albasher deputy director 
general of the grain silos and flour mills organization to sell 
saudi wheat is not difficult 
the once desolate land that produced 3000 tons of wheat in 1975 
is expected to yield 32 million tons this year 
critics charge that the project hemorrhages cash and guzzles 
water from under the desert at a rate that will dry up the precious 
resource 
however government officials say the quantity of food grown and 
its distribution mean any iraqi attempt to attack one region or 
blockade food imports could not interrupt supplies 
we dont need to buy food in an emergency said albasher 
an extremely costly subsidy program underwrote the achievement 
interestfree loans up to 5 million or more are available to 
purchase land machinery and irrigation equipment 
the dairy herd you want is in holland no problem the 
government will pay for the shipping 
basically farming is a license to make money said another 
western diplomat speaking like his colleague on condition of 
anonymity 
the government buys all the wheat produced for 400 per ton from 
large corporate farms and 533 per ton from smaller producers that 
same ton sells for about 186 on world markets 
the wheat milled into flour goes at the bargainbasement rate of 
117 per ton caterers supplying the estimated 100000 us troops 
in saudi arabia buy their supplies from the government 
the 1990 budget allocated almost 2 billion for subsidies most 
of that for agriculture 
the government started to gently apply the brakes on subsidies 
during the oil price drop of the late 1980s it would like to see 
production gradually concentrate less on wheat and more on crops 
like flowers and vegetables government officials say 
but wheat still accounts for more than 65 percent of 
agricultural production 
while petrodollars were producing huge cash reserves everyone 
supported the agricultural development idea said omar s bagour a 
professor of economics at abdul aziz university in jiddah 
now we are asking if we should have done it on such a massive 
scale whether this was the best approach 
critics worry that the center pivot method of irrigation will 
suck underground aquifers dry within 15 years they think drip 
techniques would be preferable to the trundling sprinklers that 
allow so much to evaporate 
diplomats say the subsidy program will never be eliminated 
because it was a political rather than an economic decision from 
the beginning 
it helped spread the kingdoms wealth in the central najd 
region which had neither the oil deposits of the east nor the 
trade and annual income from the vast moslem pilgrimage to mecca in 
the west 
the program also keeps the countryside populated in a country 
bigger than western europe although most of the laborers like 
everywhere in saudi arabia are asians the subsidies have even 
tempted bedouins to settle down 
among other projects the subsidies spawned the largest dairy 
farm in the world at alkharj 54 miles south of the capital 
riyadh 
the cows are sprayed with a fine mist most of the day because 
duping them into thinking they are in some drizzly northern climate 
brings forth more milk 
the 115degree temperatures outside would curdle the milk within 
hours but a special cooling system on the hightech farm keeps the 
milk around 37 degrees as it is processed 
cucumbers and tomatoes grow in greenhouses that cover more than 
an acre each the windows are whitewashed and air conditioners 
blow cool air crop yields are about three times what they were in 
the fields 
the agriculture projects are widely viewed as a miracle in the 
kingdom 
flying overhead the harsh landscape is suddenly interrupted by 
mile after mile of green 
the sight is known to be a special favorite of the king 
said one diplomat hes made the desert bloom at a price 
but its a price he can afford so why not 
