arab foreign ministers and senior officials 
are moving the arab leagues headquarters from tunisia to cairo a 
move that signals a deepening of existing regional divisions 
the decision was approved monday by 12 of the leagues 21 
members the same majority that at an arab summit earlier this 
month condemned iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
iraq and its supporters including the palestine liberation 
organization boycotted mondays meeting 
iraq said it would not abide by the decision indicating a 
further split between baghdad and its supporters and egypt and the 
11 arab states that back the transfer 
i have faith that the return of the headquarters to its site 
in cairo is necessary to maintain the role and essence of the arab 
league egyptian foreign minister esmat abdelmeguid said in his 
message opening the meeting 
egypt will cooperate and coordinate with all arab friends and 
will continue the effort to keep the arab league a home for all 
arabs at all times based on its conviction that the league is 
above all passing conflicts among the arab states 
the message was read by osama elbaz the deputy foreign 
minister abdelmeguid was unable to attend the session because of 
minor injuries suffered during a car crash friday 
the league said its major departments would move by oct 31 from 
the tunisian capital of tunis to its old site in cairo it said 
other departments should be moved from tunis to cairo by dec 31 
announcement of the relocation is a formality to complement a 
decision made in march in tunis at a regular meeting of the arab 
league council 
the league headquarters was transfered from cairo to the 
tunisian capital in 1979 in retaliation for egypts signing of the 
camp david peace treaty with israel 
egypts membership in the arab league was reinstated in 1989 
about a year after most arab counties resumed diplomatic ties with 
cairo relations had been severed in reaction to camp david 
the arab leagues attempt to project arab unity was shattered 
after iraqs invasion of kuwait egypt morocco and syria sent 
