<TEXT>
a ban on parking along 17 miles of major paris 
streets went into effect tuesday part of a campaign to ease severe 
traffic congestion 
the restrictions prohibit parking at any time along a series of 
designated red roads that form the major eastwest and 
northsouth routes a special force of 120 police and traffic 
officers was assigned to enforce the new rules 
on tuesday they limited themselves to verbal warnings but 
starting thursday will tow away the cars of offending motorists 
violators face fines of 85 
the affected routes include some of paris bestknown streets 
such as the rue du rivoli and the boulevard saint michel even 
delivery trucks are barred from stopping in some areas 
mayor jacques chirac said the restrictions are part of a plan to 
limit the use of private cars in central paris and give priority to 
public transport he said the city intends to compensate for the 
ban by providing thousands of new parking spaces in proposed 
underground garages 
some environmentalist groups have criticized the ban saying it 
will backfire by attracting more motorists with the prospect of 
less congested streets 
