its an issue of over spending richard l lesher told 
reporters at a briefing on the chambers legislative agenda 
weve said so many times that to balance the budget you dont 
have to cut spending below current levels you need to cut the 
growth in spending 
bush administration and congressional negotiators met throughout 
the weekend but were unable to meet their monday deadline for 
reaching agreement on a deficitreducing package for the fiscal 
year beginning oct 1 
without an agreement next years shortfall could surpass 250 
billion the highest ever and result in severe spending cuts on 
most federal programs under the grammrudman deficitreduction law 
lesher said the whole process is so politicized that its time 
for a political revolution hopefully led by the business 
community to demand that the problem be solved the same way all of 
us solve domestic budget problems or corporate budget problems by 
keeping spending in line with revenue 
among the items on the chambers legislative wishlist are a 
balancedbudget amendment to the constitution and enactment of 
lineitem veto authority for the president 
under current law the president must accept or reject in their 
entirety each of the 13 appropriations bills lineitem veto 
authority would permit him to throw out specific portions of the 
bills without vetoing the entire legislation 
lesher said the chamber is concerned about the effects of forced 
budget cuts on an economy that the organization predicts will fall 
into recession later this year 
we think that 100 billion in cuts would be a lot to 
swallow he said 
