<TEXT>
irans leaders are tightlipped about 
whether they will help their old adversary iraq break un 
sanctions but analysts believe tehran wont risk international 
outcry even though it wants an agreeable iraq on its border 
after talks with iraqi foreign minister tariq aziz the first 
senior official to visit tehran in 15 years the government 
announced monday it would revive full diplomatic relations with its 
former war foe 
aziz is believed to have requested that iran allow food 
medicine and other essential commodities to move across its 
730mile border with iraq in violation of the international embargo 
imposed on baghdad for its aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
iranian newspapers have argued that the country would not 
violate the sanctions by supplying food and medicine because 
humanitarian aid is permitted under the un security council 
resolution imposing the embargo 
unconfirmed reports from baghdad said the iranians already have 
allowed rice flour and wheat across the northern border 
western analysts believe iranian president hashemi rafsanjani is 
keeping everyone guessing on what iran will do in hopes of striking 
a bargain with the west in return for adhering to the embargo such 
a deal could include financial aid for iran they say 
a diplomat in tehran speaking on condition of anonymity said 
whenever weve tried to analyze their situation logically we 
found we were invariably on the wrong track 
however a western economic expert in tehran also speaking on 
condition of anonymity said smuggling along the frontier was 
difficult to control and was certain to pick up as iranians cash in 
on iraqs burgeoning black market 
anything more substantial than that would be politically and 
economically dangerous for iran because it would give the 
international community the idea that they were subverting un 
sanctions he said 
shaul bakhash a professor of history at washingtons george 
mason university said in a telephone interview it defies logic 
that the iranians would do anything to help iraq consolidate their 
hold over kuwait 
bakhash an iranian exile and former tehran newspaper editor 
has written extensively on iran 
azizs visit and the restoration of full ties came three weeks 
after iraqi president saddam hussein under increasing pressure 
from the buildup of usled forces in the gulf caved in to 
iranian conditions to formally end the nations 198088 war 
iraq granted tehran partial control of its sole access to the 
sea and withdrew its troops from iranian territory seized during 
the war 
the iranians have followed a clever policy of taking 
everything that came their way since the invasion of kuwait said 
