<TEXT>
uninsured patients and those on medicaid were 
less likely to receive three common treatments for heart disease 
than those with insurance a study of 37994 people in 
massachusetts has found 
the study examined the care of heart disease patients admitted 
to more than 100 massachusetts hospitals in 1985 
researchers looked at three common but expensive treatments 
angiography used to diagnose heart disease and bypass grafting 
and angioplasty procedures to treat blocked coronary arteries 
we found that the odds that privately insured patients 
received angiography were 80 percent higher than uninsured 
patients the odds were 40 percent higher for bypass grafting and 
28 percent higher for angioplasty the authors wrote in 
wednesdays journal of the american medical association 
medicaid patients experienced odds similar to those of 
uninsured patients for receiving angiography and bypass but had 48 
percent lower odds of receiving angioplasty they wrote 
this is very disturbing dr mark wenneker a health policy 
researcher at new england medical center in boston said tuesday 
its very possible that the uninsured and medicaid people 
needed these procedures and didnt get them but we dont know 
that said wenneker the lead researcher 
on the other hand equally disturbing is the possibility that 
there may have been no difference in what happened to insured 
versus the uninsured which raises the question of whether these 
procedures were actually even necessary wenneker said in a 
telephone interview 
in an angiography dye is injected into coronary arteries to 
determine if there is any blockage 
if blockage is found an openheart bypass operation may be 
done grafting a vessel from another part of the body to bypass the 
blockage and allow enough blood to reach the heart 
angioplasty is an alternative operation in which a small balloon 
is inflated inside the blocked vessel to push the clot into the 
vessel wall and reduce the blockage 
angiography and angioplasty each generally cost more than 
1000 while bypass operations usually cost several thousand 
dollars wenneker said 
the three are considered definitive procedures necessary to 
diagnose and treat heart disease wenneker said 
the researchers however did not examine the patients outcomes 
to see if any of them might have died or their conditions worsened 
after not receiving the procedures wenneker said 
they also did not determine whether it was the decision of the 
physician hospital or patient to forgo the procedures 
their study did conclude that the patients insurance status was 
a major factor and that the procedures were done less often on 
those with lower incomes and it suggests that quality of care may 
depend on a patients insurance status 
although the central mission of many hospitals was once the 
provision of charity care rising costs and an increasingly 
competitive health care marketplace have influenced the willingness 
of hospitals to care for uninsured patients the researchers 
wrote 
in an accompanying editorial dr james todd the amas 
executive vice president said changes are needed in the financing 
and delivering of health care to make sure treatment does not 
depend on economics 
many hypotheses could be advanced to explain these differences 
but all would raise the issue that the volume and location of care 
seem related to the availability of funding todd wrote 
the medical profession stands ready to participate in any 
program that brings equity to the system he said it does not 
stand ready to abandon its advocacy for patients in the name of 
expediency 
</TEXT>
