<TEXT>
the deficit in the countrys broadest measure 
of foreign trade rose slightly in the apriljune quarter to 2184 
billion still the secondbest showing in six years the government 
reported tuesday 
however private economists forecast that the deficit will head 
sharply higher in the months ahead as the persian gulf crisis 
boosts americas foreign oil bill and cuts into americans overseas 
earnings 
the commerce department report showed that the nations current 
account trade deficit was up a slight 08 percent from a first 
quarter gap of 2167 billion which had been the best showing 
since a 212 billion deficit in the first three months of 1984 
the current account is the most important trade statistic 
because it measures not only trade in merchandise but also in 
services and investment flows between countries 
the strong showing in the second quarter resulted from a record 
level of us merchandise sales balancing a deterioration in 
investment earnings which went into deficit for the first time in 
a year 
analysts forecast that the deficit for the rest of this year 
would rise as a result of the crisis in the middle east 
under their scenario higher oil prices will boost americas 
import bill while slower worldwide growth as a result of the 
turmoil will cut down on american export sales as well as dampen 
overseas earnings by us companies 
our economy is now tied more than ever to foreign growth 
slower growth overseas will reduce demand for us exports and 
reduce our earnings on overseas investments said stephen cooney 
director of international investment for the national association 
of manufacturers 
david wyss senior financial economist at drimcgraw hill said 
the trade deficit could widen by 25 percent in coming months 
because of the fallout from the persian gulf that forecast would 
represent a blow to bush administration hopes for a continued 
strong trade performance to bolster a weak domestic economy 
wyss predicted the trade deficit would start narrowing again by 
the second half of next year as oil prices begin to come down but 
he said this estimate was dependent on events in the persian gulf 
if shooting starts then oil prices go higher and the trade 
deficit gets a lot worse he said 
for the second quarter the merchandise trade deficit narrowed a 
sharp 141 percent to 226 billion reflecting a big drop in oil 
prices and a record level of exports 
the surplus in the services account which reflects such things 
as tourism and payments for services running from architects to 
lawyers totaled 608 billion up 13 percent from the first 
quarter 
however these improvements were offset by the fact that the 
investment category moved into deficit for the first time in a 
year the deficit in the second quarter was 637 million compared 
to a surplus of 20 billion in the first quarter 
the other category in the current account unilateral transfers 
such as foreign aid and pension payments to americans living 
overseas showed a deficit of 471 billion in the second quarter 
39 percent larger than the first quarter deficit 
even with the improvement in the first six months the united 
states started the 1990s in a vastly different position from a 
decade earlier 
then america was the largest creditor nation it ran surpluses 
in its current account as the earnings on its overseas investments 
were enough to offset perennial deficits in merchandise trade 
but as americans handed over billions of dollars to foreigners 
to pay for imported merchandise the investment cushion eroded and 
disappeared altogether in 1985 when the united states became a net 
debtor for the first time in 71 years 
that means that foreigners now own more in us assets than 
americans own overseas a development which has led some to fear 
america is losing control of its economic destiny to foreigners 
at the end of 1989 the countrys net debtor position was put at 
6637 billion up a sharp 25 percent from the previous year many 
analysts believe it will hit 1 trillion before beginning to 
improve 
