<TEXT>
more than 250000 seriously mentally ill 
americans have been left untreated and are living miserable 
sometimes violent lives on the streets and in shelters and jails 
according to a report tuesday by two advocacy groups 
in all one researcher said about half of the estimated 2 
million people who have a serious mental illness are not receiving 
treatment 
the report lays much of the blame on psychiatrists and 
psychologists many of whom the groups say were trained with public 
funds but have abandoned the public system for more lucrative 
private practice 
the advocacy groups public citizen and the national alliance 
for the mentally ill also fault the priorities of many public 
programs that they said spend too much of their resources providing 
such services as stress management instead of treating people with 
severe mental illnesses 
care for the seriously mentally ill is a national disaster 
said laurie flynn executive director of the alliance 
dr sidney wolfe who heads the health research group of public 
citizen founded by consumer advocate ralph nader said some 
communities have built great model programs therefore he 
said it becomes more and more intolerable when others dont 
adopt them 
the american psychiatric association objected strongly to the 
reports snide scapegoating statements about psychiatrists 
saying they have had a historic commitment to providing 
services for the severely mentally ill who rely on the public 
system twenty percent of psychiatrists work in the public sector 
which the apa said is a higher percentage than in any other area of 
medicine 
apa spokesman john blamphin said psychiatrists would not be 
opposed to donating an hour of their time a week to public 
programs as the report recommends if thats also required of 
others working in the health field 
the report care of the seriously mentally ill a rating of 
state programs evaluates the services provided by each state and 
scores them accordingly the groups began this biennial review in 
1986 
the report assesses hospital services outpatient and community 
support services vocational rehabilitation housing services and 
programs for seriously emotionally disturbed children 
vermont ranked highest scoring 17 of a possible 25 points new 
hampshire and rhode island each scored 16 connecticut and ohio 15 
each and colorado 14 
hawaii finished last as it did in the 1986 and 1988 reports 
with 2 points idaho and wyoming each scored 3 mississippi and 
montana 4 each and nevada and texas 5 each 
overall the new england states tended to score among the 
highest while more western states were at the bottom of the list 
we think that there is kind of a culture of caring that has 
grown up in some states and not in others clearly this is 
strongest in new england and weakest in the west said dr e 
fuller torrey a psychiatrist with public citizens health research 
group 
in the west with texas as a good example its kind of a 
macho mentality youre supposed to take care of yourself he 
said 
all told he said as many as one million seriously mentally ill 
people nationwide are not actively receiving treatment 
the report said one of the major reasons the public system is so 
lacking is that mental health professionals many of whom were 
trained with the help of government funds dont want to treat the 
seriously mentally ill 
rather the report said most psychologists and psychiatrists 
spend their time in their offices counseling people with 
relatively minor mental health problems torrey said 
since the federal government began subsidizing training of 
mental health professionals in 1945 the number of psychiatrists 
has grown from 3000 to 40000 the report said the number of 
psychologists has risen from 4200 to 70000 and psychiatric social 
workers from 2000 to about 80000 
to illustrate his point torrey said that while princeton nj 
has one psychiatrist for every 250 people jersey city nj has 
one for every 13600 people 
the professionals who have been trained with public funds have 
gone off to private practice and left the seriously mentally ill in 
the public sector without any care he said 
the gap is being filled by foreign medical students who now 
constitute about twothirds of the psychiatrists in public 
psychiatric hospitals and clinics in the united states the report 
said 
