<TEXT>
the failure of a natural gas pipeline company 
to make sure a 16inch pipeline was securely buried beneath the 
gulf of mexico caused a fiery accident last year that killed 11 
crew members of a fishing boat the national traffic safety board 
said tuesday 
the safety board also said that the failure of the office of 
pipeline safety to require pipeline operators to inspect and 
maintain submerged pipelines contributed to the accident in shallow 
waters a halfmile off sabine texas 
but it said the pipeline safety office needs more personnel and 
resources to accomplish its mission 
the board said that while the fishing boat the northumberland 
was either very close to or penetrating the sea bottom at the time 
of the accident on oct 3 1989 the ship was not responsible 
because it was operating in its normal area and at a reasonable 
speed 
the accident the board said would not have occurred had 
the natural gas pipeline co of america maintained the pipeline 
at the depth required by the permit issued by the us army corps 
of engineers 
a spokesman for the company which has headquarters in lombard 
ill said there would be no comment until officials had a chance 
to review the safety boards conclusions 
in more than 20 recommendations the safety board an arm of the 
department of transportation urged a program be put into operation 
to inspect the companys submerged pipelines and to maintain them 
in accordance with permits requiring them to be safely buried 
the board has no enforcement powers but can only make 
recommendations to governmental agencies and private companies for 
safety improvements 
the board urged safety programs be established to warn vessels 
of the dangers of submerged pipelines and said navigation charts 
should be revised to warn mariners that submerged pipelines may not 
be safely buried 
in discussing the accident safety board members said there are 
more than 18000 miles of submerged pipelines in the gulf of mexico 
alone but that the exact length of the system or the precise 
location of all of its components is not known 
there are no records to verify how many miles of pipeline are 
out in the gulf said board member susan m coughlin 
she questioned whether actual inspection of the pipeline system 
should begin before promised technology is developed to do the job 
without the costly and time consuming use of divers 
but other members said the board has an obligation to the safety 
of seafarers to urge that work begin now to see that submerged 
pipelines are in fact safely buried 
the safety board said that inspection by divers after the 
accident showed that while the pipeline should have been buried 
some nine feet below the sea bed it was in fact lying on its 
surface 
when the northumberland hit and ruptured it the safety board 
said natural gas from the high pressure pipeline was released 
and ignited engulfing the vessel in flames within seconds 
