<TEXT>
citrus growers eager to bounce back from a 
subpar harvest got some good news tuesday when federal agriculture 
officials dropped a 6yearold quarantine 
floridas billiondollar citrus industry hoping for a sunnier 
future after a crippling christmas freeze also welcomed an 
optimistic report on increased citrus planting 
the us agriculture department announced that as of sept 18 it 
will officially remove the remaining citruscanker quarantine 
restrictions imposed in september 1984 
we were pleased to see it said dan gunter executive 
director of the florida department of citrus this will open up 
all the markets to florida it was time for the usda to 
deregulate 
federal quarantine restrictions came after an outbreak of a 
leafspotting disease in dozens of citrus nurseries it was 
believed to be a rapidly spreading asiatic strain of citrus canker 
which can devastate groves 
more than 20 million young trees were uprooted and burned 
before scientists determined that the disease was not spreading to 
mature groves and did not constitute a major threat to fruit or to 
other citrusproducing states 
restrictions were gradually relaxed after followup research 
showed that the disease was only distantly related to asiatic 
canker 
lack of faith in florida citrus brought on by the canker 
quarantine cost growers dearly said bobby mckown executive vice 
president of florida citrus mutual the largest growers trade 
association in the state 
he called it a major step forward for the citrus industry 
its been a long six years since the quarantine was first imposed 
meanwhile a biennial survey conducted by state and federal 
officials showed a 5 percent increase in citrus acreage despite 
nearly 86000 acres lost because of the christmas freeze 
thats good news a very encouraging report gunter said 
commercial citrus acreage increased to 732767 acres 5 percent 
more than the 697929 acres reported in 1988 according to the 
report 
growers planted 120696 acres in 1988 and 1989 they lost 85858 
acres of trees most of it to the december freeze leaving a net 
gain of 34838 
the 198990 orange harvest projected before the december freeze 
at 130 million 90pound boxes came in at about 110 million boxes 
it was the decades secondlowest production 
the grapefruit crop of about 36 million boxes was the smallest 
since the 196768 season 
the canker scare prompted other citrus states including texas 
and california to ban imports of florida fruit that was not 
inspected and treated before being shipped 
connie riherd assistant director of the florida agriculture 
departments division of plant industry said she hoped that other 
citrusproducing states take the federal lead and not impose 
their own regulations against florida fruit 
the wealth of biological information that has been reviewed 
by federal and state scientists shows that the nursery strain of 
the disease is not of quarantine significance mrs riherd said 
the cankereradication effort led to some 60 lawsuits by nursery 
owners who suffered losses because of the destruction of their 
young trees at last report these lawsuits totaled about 200 
million and the state was still trying to negotiate with litigants 
and impose some courtordered settlements 
the cost of the cankereradication battle to the industry and 
state and federal agencies exceeded 100 million 
this shows positive results following a major freeze said 
harry whittaker of the florida agricultural statistics service 
which compiled the survey results we see continued interest by 
growers in new plantings 
