<TEXT>
a boeing 727 jet carrying 18 
people apparently crashed southeast of newfoundland on tuesday 
after straying off course over the atlantic ocean officials said 
the faucett airliner was en route from the mediterranean island 
of malta to miami with a refueling stop scheduled for gander 
newfoundland said an airline operations manager in miami 
faucett officials said the 18 on board were all from peru where 
the airline is based but that one of the crewmen lived in miami 
transport canada spokesman lily abbass said the jet was off 
course and was believed to have gone down tuesday afternoon about 
250 miles southeast of st johns she said the crew declared a 
lowfuel emergency 30 minutes after it was due in gander she said 
the message was relayed by two us aircraft 
a spokesman for the search and rescue coordination center in 
halifax said tuesday night that a weak signal from the jets 
emergency transmitter was picked up by satellite after radio 
contact was lost 
however rescue officials said each time the satellite made a 
pass over the area the signal seemed to come from a different 
location sometimes hundreds of miles apart 
rescue officials assumed the jet ditched in the sea and 
dispatched three aurora airplanes and three labrador helicopters to 
the area where the plane was last heard from weather conditions 
were described as good and the seas calm 
some of the planes arrived in the area tuesday evening but 
spotted nothing two coast guard vessels two fisheries patrol 
vessels and two destroyers were also dispatched to the search area 
the boeing 727 no longer in production was designed to 
withstand a landing at sea and can float for several hours boeing 
spokesman tom cole said from renton wash 
the jetliner stopped in keflavik iceland en route but a 
refueling supervisor at keflavik said there was no problem during 
the stopover 
jens gudmundsson supervisor of the air traffic control center 
in reykjavik iceland speculated the pilot got lost 
nobody knows why the aircraft lost track said betty 
mcdaniel a faucett spokeswoman in miami 
the jet had been under contract to air malta since may and was 
being returned to miami for service in the summer months according 
to jose lazaga the airlines vice president for marketing in miami 
he said the 18 aboard included crew and relatives of the 
airlines employees 
those in the plane included an infant and up to four women said 
ms mcdaniel 
faucett is a limabased carrier that operates both commercial 
and cargo flights 
