<TEXT>
women in the armed forces appear almost four 
times as likely as men to be subjected to sexual harassment the 
pentagon reported tuesday 
according to a survey of 38000 military men and women the most 
common form of harassment was teasing or suggestive remarks but 15 
percent of the women and 2 percent of the men said they had been 
pressured for sexual favors 
five percent of the females and 1 percent of the male 
respondents reported actual or attempted rape or sexual assault 
said the pentagons summary of findings 
the survey was ordered in 1988 by thensecretary frank carlucci 
in response to a recommendation from a task force set up to advise 
the defense department on women in the military 
survey respondents in the four armed services and the coast 
guard were queried between december 1988 and april 1989 about 60 
percent of those contacted returned replies 
there was virtually no difference between female and male 
response rates but actual numbers were not given the proportion 
of women varies from service to service but they are about 11 
percent of todays 2 million people in the armed services 
overall the pentagon said 22 percent of active duty personnel 
indicated they had experienced some form of sexual harassment 
ranging from sexual jokes to actual assault while at work the 
previous year 
christopher jehn assistant secretary for force management and 
personnel said the department was concerned about the incidents 
reported and was carefully reviewing the findings 
jehn said in a statement he was heartened by evidence in the 
study that most of those who had been harassed also believed that 
we are moving in good faith to do something about it 
the survey first to consider active duty personnel only will 
provide a statistical benchmark for use in evaluating the 
effectiveness of policies designed to prevent sexual harassment 
the survey found that 64 percent of the women but only 17 
percent of the men had experienced some form of sexual harassment 
on the job in the previous year 
other findings 
eightytwo percent of those women victims and 74 percent of 
their men counterparts said the harassment took the form of sexual 
teasing jokes remarks or questions 
sixtynine percent of the female victims and 54 percent of the 
male victims said it took the form of suggestive looks gestures or 
body language 
sixty percent of the women victims and 51 percent of the men 
victims reported touching leaving over cornering pinching or 
being brushed against in a deliberately sexual manner 
the study said perpetrators of the experiences described by 
females were men acting alone 75 percent of the time while 22 
percent of the incidents were brought on by more than one man 
incidents started by women were not mentioned 
among men victims 50 percent of the perpetrators were women 
acting alone and only 10 percent involved a group of women but the 
other 40 percent of the incidents directed against men were caused 
by men alone or in a group with other men and women 
the study said nearly threequarters of the respondents said 
policies had been established at their posts to reduce sexual 
harassment about a quarter of the personnel either did not know of 
any such policies and believed that none had been put in place 
</TEXT>
