<TEXT>
eastern europes tilt toward the west and 
japans economic ascent in the east appear to be nudging americans 
out of a longstanding apathy toward foreign languages 
theres definitely a boom going on in language studies in this 
country said charles stansfield of the center for applied 
linguistics in washington the number and percentage of people 
studying are as high as theyve ever been 
about a third of us high school students are taking a foreign 
language class this fall stansfield estimated reflecting a steady 
rise since the 1970s when the figure was as low as 23 percent 
college students and adults also appear to be more immersed in 
language studies educators say although recent comprehensive 
statistics are not available in those categories 
educators however wonder how long foreign languages will 
remain a la mode 
the united states is solidly entrenched as the most monolingual 
of all developed countries language training professionals use 
such words as abysmal and shameful to describe americans 
foreignlanguage skills 
the explosive growth of english in eastern europe and its 
acknowledged status as the regions no 2 tongue could give 
americans even more of an excuse to stick with english 
but developments of the past few years show foreign language 
studies on the upswing in the united states 
for the first time since the mid1970s more than a million 
college students were studying foreign languages in 1986 the 
latest year for which nationwide statistics are available 
japanese chinese russian and since the fall of the berlin wall 
german all have gained experts say 
consider 
thirty states have either begun or increased foreign language 
requirements for their public schools in the last 10 years said 
jamie draper acting director of the joint national committee for 
languages in washington 
in at least five states connecticut louisiana new york 
north carolina and virginia half of all elementary and secondary 
school students are now studying a foreign language according to 
the american council on the teaching of foreign languages no state 
could make such a claim a decade ago and the council said arizona 
and california will join the group soon 
japanese language enrollment tripled the past four to five 
years to more than 30000 said richard lambert director of the 
national foreign language center at johns hopkins university more 
than 300 us schools now have programs in japanese compared with 
only a few a decade ago 
michigan recently required that all high schools offer courses 
in japanese and under a new pilot program children in a handful 
of communities mostly in california hawaii and new york are 
taught japanese beginning in first grade 
german which gradually declined in popularity in the 1980s 
has led a resurgence of some eastern european languages in the 
months since the berlin wall and the iron curtain were yanked down 
in the last year enrollment is up 52 percent for german and 44 
percent for russian at new yorkbased berlitz international inc 
the largest private language school in the country across 
manhattan the world trade institute language center says german 
enrollment is up 30 percent to 40 percent neither company would 
release enrollment figures 
