<TEXT>
americans often exhibit a basic instinct about 
financial cycles especially the down side of them showing by 
their behavior that they sense trouble before it descends on the 
economy in general 
they are you might say at the very front line of the economic 
battle for survival and out there in the foxholes they pick up the 
little hints and signals of rising prices job insecurity credit 
strains and the like 
their test is a practical one if the money in the wallet 
doesnt go as far as it used to then inflation is creeping higher 
if their neighbors work week is reduced to four days they think 
about recession and their own job security 
presented with such evidence consumers in the past consumed 
less read price tags that might have been ignored earlier paid 
down credit lines postponed vacations decided to use the old car 
just one more year 
some evidence of hunkering down had begun to appear in the 
economic statistics over the past few months including an 
improving savings rate but then came a report that at first 
glance seems to blow away the thesis 
that report consumer debt grew during july at an annual rate of 
74 percent the fastest in nine months and most of that 
increase was in revolving credit which includes the use of bank 
and other credit cards 
it provokes the question has their instinctive intelligence 
about such matters deserted the consumer or is the growth in the 
use of credit card debt an indication that todays consumer is 
forced to the wall 
once not long ago it was impossible for consumers to obtain 
credit that would permit them to spend in defiance of a downturn 
it was a mechanical matter that is no bank would give them credit 
with which to spend 
over the past decade that situation has changed totally almost 
no consumer needs to fill out a loan application one of those 
oldfashioned questionnaires that asked how much you made how much 
you owed what the money was needed for 
instead they have a prearranged line of credit with the 
lender who quickly delivers the money and agrees not to ask any 
embarrassing questions such as whether the borrower is employed or 
whether he intends to repay 
the oddity of this is that while lenders have created an 
easycredit society for consumers they and their federal 
regulators have progressively cracked down on loans for healthy 
business enterprises 
a crackdown on production small as it might be eventually 
leads to an imbalance of supply and demand but coupled with a 
simultaneous spur to consumption through easy credit it 
conceivably could create serious problems 
the statistical evidence leaves unresolved the reason why 
consumer credit grew so much in july 
it might just be additional evidence of strains on the consumer 
wallet as the economy slows which is bad enough but it could be 
something else too 
it could be an indication that a lot of american families are 
heading into a deeper hole than if they didnt have the easy use of 
credit heading into a situation from which it wont be easy to 
recover 
