<TEXT>
jet fuel costs have soared since iraq invaded 
kuwait but its anyones guess whether an airline ticket will cost 
you more or less in coming months 
indications are that theyre going up said raymond e 
neidl an airline analyst with dillon read amp co inc airlines 
are getting around that by jacking up the basic fare and then 
offering various discounts 
for the time being some fares are rising and others are falling 
in a phenomenon that neidl described monday as turmoil in 
pricing 
the latest price changes are a temporary round of cheaper fares 
to europe 
trans world and northwest announced over the weekend that they 
were offering some special low fares on transatlantic flights for 
fall and winter tickets purchased by sept 21 on monday airlines 
saying they would follow suit included usair and pan am 
other carriers were studying the overseas fare cut they are 
also keeping an eye on what comes from a round of domestic fare 
increases that were announced recently by pan am and alaska air 
group 
since the persian gulf crisis began the price airlines pay for 
jet fuel has shot up some 40 percent from around 60 cents per 
gallon to between 80 and 90 cents per gallon 
that rise puts the sluggish airline industry in a bind if crude 
oil maintains its current high price airlines can expect to pay an 
additional 45 billion per year for fuel according to an industry 
group the air transport association 
finding a way to pay for more expensive fuel is not easy any 
airline that goes out on a limb by raising fares runs the risk of 
losing business in the highly competitive market 
last month the major us carriers said they would raise their 
domestic fares by 53 percent in response to the inflated cost of 
jet fuel but analysts and industry sources said the higher fares 
would not pick up the entire increase in the industrys jet fuel 
tab 
two airlines then decided they would charge fliers more money on 
domestic flights 
alaska air announced an additional 47 percent fare increase to 
take effect oct 1 and pan am announced an additional 44 percent 
fare increase to take effect sept 18 
neidl said alaska air can probably pull off its increase 
because it is a regional carrier that serves some alaska 
destinations that other airlines cannot reach he found pan ams 
move intriguing 
pan am is never going to get away with that if other airlines 
dont match it neidl said monday theyre going to have a hard 
time holding that because theyre going to lose traffic 
domestically pan am is too small to be a price leader he said 
pan am spokeswoman elizabeth hlinko would not say whether her 
carrier is concerned about scaring off travelers 
this is something were monitoring ms hlinko said at 
this point were planning on putting it the increase into 
effect 
other airlines said monday they were watching pan ams move but 
none would say whether it was considering a similar increase 
before we would strongly consider a fare increase we would 
have to see jet fuel costs remain high northwest spokesman doug 
miller said we certainly dont want to raise fares you always 
run the risk of inhibiting traffic 
neidl viewed the cheaper fares to europe as a temporary 
marketing strategy that airlines often use in an attempt to lure 
discretionary travelers nonbusiness passengers who might 
decide on a relatively short notice to take an overseas vacation 
this happens all the time during the slow seasons he said 
you dont want to fill up all your seats that way 
after oct 1 international flights might start costing more 
the international air transport association recently agreed to fare 
increases of 5 percent to 8 percent that are still being processed 
by various governments 
some us airlines plan to go along with those increases while 
others were not yet ready to say what they will do 
</TEXT>
