<TEXT>
two federal bank regulators say they are still 
at odds over the amount of capital that banks should maintain to 
avoid a savings and loanlike debacle in the banking industry 
in testimony before a senate panel monday the controller of the 
currency and the head of the federal deposit insurance corp said 
their dispute has narrowed since january but they still disagree 
firmly on lowering the capital standards for all banks 
fdic chairman l william seidman said a drop in federal 
requirements so that banks must maintain capital standards of at 
least 3 percent of assets should be limited to only the healthiest 
of the nations 12400 banks 
but controller of the currency robert l clarke thinks raising 
the standard any higher would supercede plans to make a riskbased 
capital standard the primary focus for evaluating the adequacy of a 
banks capital 
by the end of this year all banks and thrifts will be required 
to have 725 percent capital to riskadjusted assets that ratio 
will grow to 8 percent by the end of 1992 
seidman told the senate banking committee that he and clarke 
agree on many more things than we disagree on but i dont 
think we can continue with these differences without causing real 
harm to the system 
capital is the basic yardstick for measuring a financial 
institutions soundness the more capital a bank has the more 
losses it can absorb without failing conversely the less capital 
the more likely losses could force a failure 
legislation passed by congress last year set minimum capital 
standards for savings and loans but there is no minimum set by law 
for the amount of cash and assets easily converted into cash banks 
must have to offset the risk of loans and investments 
currently the federal reserve board the fdic and the office of 
the controller of the currency have a gentlemans agreement that 
banks must maintain a leverage ratio capital to total assets of 
6 percent 
the fed has adopted new standards effective dec 31 that would 
require the most highlyrated banks to have at least a 3 percent 
ratio of capital to total assets with other banks required to have 
another 1 percent or 2 percent in capital 
seidman said he was willing to go along with that as a 
compromise although the fdic chairman preferred the ratio up around 
45 percent 
but the occ which oversees some 4000 national banks around the 
country wants to set the requirement at 3 percent for all banks 
seidman said that was too low and would reduce the capital 
requirements of some 10000 banks 
there are three lines of defense in keeping industry losses to 
a minimum and avoiding a taxpayer bailout sen donald w riegle 
jr dmich the committee chairman said at the hearings start 
the first is careful lending practices at banks and thrifts he 
said the second is the capital maintained by financial 
institutions and the third is the federal deposit insurance fund 
asked by riegle if the agencies could settle their differences 
controller of the currency robert clarke said the differences are 
extremely minimal 
but seidman shook his head during clarkes answer 
this disagreement may sound like regulators splitting hairs 3 
percent and 45 percent theres only a 15 percent difference but 
it is a very material difference when one looks at the banking 
system insisted seidman 
at 3 percent he said substantially all smaller banks would 
have a lower minimum standard eliminating a check on financial 
institutions with potential exposure to interest rate risks 
riegle asked seidman and clarke who were joined at the hearing 
by fed governor wayne d angell and timothy ryan director of the 
office of thrift supervision to try and work out their differences 
and report back to him in 30 days 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

