<TEXT>
michael milken who pleaded guilty to six 
felonies to settle securities fraud charges is expected to face a 
slew of new allegations the government hopes will induce a judge to 
stiffen his prison sentence 
the government agreed not to indict milken for any other 
financial crimes when it accepted his guilty plea in april but 
federal courts have allowed prosecutors to air a range of charges 
at sentencing that a defendant hasnt been convicted of or pleaded 
guilty to 
milken the former head of drexel burnham lambert incs 
highyield bond department admitted six felonies and agreed to pay 
600 million in penalties to settle a 98count fraud and 
racketeering indictment 
attorneys said monday the government will detail a host of other 
unproven crimes before us district judge kimba wood as she 
prepares to sentence milken oct 1 
wood could refuse to consider any new charges outright as 
happened in a case before another judge this year or she could 
scheduled a hearing on the claims that might include testimony by 
admitted inside trader ivan boesky 
assistant us attorney john carroll said the government was to 
present its report to wood on thursday he declined to comment on 
the contents but stressed the governments right to go beyond 
milkens guilty plea 
under the plea agreement signed by milken the government can 
bring to the courts attention conduct that was not included in 
the plea milken also agreed not to dispute making the governments 
final sentencing report public 
the justice department agreed not to request a specific 
sentence milken faces a maximum 28 years in prison the charges to 
which he pleaded guilty were not among the most serious in the 
indictment 
milken is entitled to rebut any charges the government may make 
in its sentencing report and can defend himself at a hearing which 
either side can ask the judge to hold 
attorneys for former milken associates who cooperated with the 
governments nearly fouryear investigation said they had been told 
that prosecutors planned to bring their full case against milken to 
woods attention 
weve gotten wind of such a hearing said aubrey harwell 
jr who represents former drexel bond salesman cary maultasch 
we understand the government is contemplating calling 
numerous witnesses 
a spokesman for milken declined to comment 
such hearings which can include evidence testimony and 
crossexamination as at a trial are rare attorneys said a milken 
hearing could last up to three months and feature testimony by 
boesky who served two years in prison after settling insider 
trading charges boesky was milkens chief accuser 
earlier this year us district judge pierre n leval refused 
to admit charges that former goldman sachs amp co arbitrager robert 
m freeman committed 20 crimes in addition to a single charge of 
insider trading he admitted 
the government of course had the opportunity to charge the 
defendant with those 20 crimes instead it made a plea bargain with 
the defendant agreeing to prosecute this single charge he 
wrote 
but leval added that it was not necessarily improper for the 
government to point to other offenses adding to its call for a 
hefty sentence the milken case may qualify because of its scope 
and the wide public attention it has generated 
attorneys said no matter how devastating the new charges milken 
would be unlikely to request a public hearing because testimony 
could add to the hundreds of pending civil lawsuits stemming from 
his crimes 
the sentencing report is less damaging than having all the 
evidence laid out said one attorney who asked not to be named 
it provides a road map to civil plaintiffs it doesnt give it to 
them on a silver platter 
the rationale for allowing unindicted criminal allegations is 
that a judge should consider negative information at sentencing as 
well as positive information such as letters from friends 
a federal appeals court in 1980 endorsed the practice in an 
organized crime case the decision was upheld by the supreme court 
even though many lawyers maintain its unfair to defendants 
since when in this country can you go to jail for things a 
jury hasnt found you guilty of at a hearing where hearsay is 
admissible and by a standard that is less than proof beyond a 
reasonable doubt asked gerald lefcourt attorney for former 
drexel trader bruce newberg who was indicted along with milken 
last year and convicted in a separate case 
