<TEXT>
federal regulators have blocked columbia 
savings amp loan from selling 3 billion of its junk bonds to a group 
of canadian and hong kong investors 
regulators said monday that the troubled thrift failed to seek 
any allcash bids columbia chief edward g harshfield said in a 
brief statement that the thrift obtained the most favorable bid 
the office of thrift supervision also said it could not approve 
the sale in its current form because the troubled thrift neglected 
to seek an adequate number of bids for the junk bond portfolio 
columbia at one time had the thrift industrys largest portfolio 
of highyield highrisk junk bonds the thrift is based in beverly 
hills 
the los angeles times in todays editions quoted unidentified 
sources as saying l william seidman would support a cash deal in 
which columbia gets rid of the junk bonds for good 
seidman chairs the federal deposit insurance corp and the 
resolution trust corp the agency formed last year to handle 
failing thrifts 
