<TEXT>
a major japanese company has begun marketing 
something consumers have long awaited a videocassette recorder 
that automatically cuts out commercials even the makers own 
and while sales have been good the product has raised the ire 
of television networks which argue that the possibility of fewer 
people viewing commercials may prompt advertisers to pay less for 
air time 
advertisements for the vcrs which are made by mitsubishi 
electric corp and are priced from 600 to 1200boast that with 
this convenient function you can automatically cut commercials 
and enjoy the programs you want to watch without the ads 
the technology is aimed mainly at producing uninterrupted 
recordings of western movies which are often broadcast on two 
audio channels a main channel for the japaneselanguage 
soundtrack and a subchannel for the original language 
the bilingual programming was introduced on major network 
schedules in 1978 after being developed by the japan broadcasting 
corp about a decade earlier 
special signals during these broadcasts which are usually 
reserved for movies news and foreignmade programs serve as a 
cue for the new machines telling them when to start and stop 
recording 
such programs however account for only a fraction of the total 
broadcasting fare rendering mitsubishis autocut capability 
useless for much of the days programming 
even so the idea has made television networks nervous 
two months after mitsubishis videocassette recorder hit the 
market in april japans largest privately owned network the tokyo 
broadcasting system began mixing electronic static with its signal 
to foil the autocut 
if viewers want to edit out commercials themselves they are 
free to do so said tbs spokesman akitsuna furuya but we 
believe that if taping is to be done it should accurately reflect 
what we broadcast 
furuya added that the technology doesnt just edit out 
commercials it also cuts out the movie reviews that come at the 
beginning and end of the broadcast 
the national association of commercial broadcasters a 
federation of japans commercial stations also expressed 
reservations 
commercial television is based on advertising so we obviously 
are against the idea of cutting out ads said an official with 
the association who requested anonymity 
they dont have much of a share in the market yet so we 
havent really been forced to take any position either way but if 
other companies started making similar machines we would probably 
have to protest the official said 
mitsubishi spokesman masahiro suekuni said that when developing 
autocut mitsubishi was also aware that it too could be the 
victim of adediting 
but we decided that was something which couldnt be avoided 
he added that mitsubishi doesnt expect autocut to have 
much effect on broadcasters 
most people will continue to watch tv as it is broadcast he 
said 
the japan video association says nearly 70 percent of all 
japanese homes have a vcr one of the highest ratios in the world 
while not giving exact figures suekuni said mitsubishi has a 
doubledigit share but still lags behind other home electronics 
giants like matsushita which makes panasonic and national brand 
products 
because of the high percentage of homes that already have vcrs 
producers are finding it increasingly difficult to keep sales up 
and have had to seek out new options such as autocut or 
lower prices 
its a slow market in general suekuni said but sales of 
videos with the autocut function have been better than average 
for a new product 
</TEXT>
