<TEXT>
a computer services company said tuesday it 
would appeal a judges ruling that it violated an ibm copyright for 
a key component needed to run ibms largest computers 
us district judge thomas n oneill jr in philadelphia ruled 
friday that allenmyland inc violated ibms copyright for the 
microcode needed to operate its 3090 series mainframes oneill 
is scheduled to determine damages at a later date 
allenmyland based in broomall pa reconfigures international 
business machines corp computers for customers such as splitting 
large computers into smaller versions 
oneill found that the company in dividing a computer copied 
ibms microcode for one of the two computers that resulted 
microcode is the circuitry in a computers central processor 
that translates programming commands into language recognized by 
the processor 
under a contract with ibm allenmyland was required to obtain 
the second set of code from ibm said ibm spokesman brian doyle 
the judge also found that allenmyland misrepresented to 
customers that this second set of code came from ibm doyle said 
allenmylands president larry allen said his company contends 
that microcode is part and parcel of the machine and that 
customers should be allowed to alter that 
he said the copied code was used solely in computers owned by 
the same customer from which the copy was made and that 
allenmyland did not sell the copied code to other customers 
in a blow to ibm oneill also ruled that ibms pricing of the 
microcode violates a 34yearold consent decree ibm entered into 
with the justice department relating to competition doyle said ibm 
would appeal that ruling 
</TEXT>
