cocoa producing countries were advised tuesday to 
reduce drastically their areas under cultivation because of grim 
prospects if output continues growing as it has in recent years 
increasing oversupply and persistently low prices are indicated 
for cocoa under three of four projected scenarios in a study by the 
international cocoa organization and the genevabased united 
nations conference on trade and development 
the market already has a heavy surplus following six seasons of 
overproduction world stocks are at a record 137 million tons 
according to estimates released last month by the londonbased 
cocoa organization 
in february the price of cocoa dropped to its lowest in 14 
years 
experts are projecting another world surplus in the 199091 
season which begins oct 1 
under the baseline scenario projected by the study world cocoa 
production will peak at 31 million tons in 20012002 compared 
with estimated output of 2361 million tons in 199091 
the biggest increases are foreseen in southeast asia up 62 
percent and africa up 32 percent particularly in the ivory 
coast the worlds biggest producer 
growth in latin america is projected at only 10 percent because 
output is expected to fall in brazil 
demand should also grow through the period the study says but 
not to a projected peak of 31 million tons until 2005 use in 
198990 is estimated at 2211 million tons 
