news conference held by the american bankers association 
esposito noted that the banking industry had almost 26 billion 
in profits last year while the savings and loan industry lost more 
than 19 billion he also said the threat to the banks by 
potentially uncollectable loans to third world nations had 
diminished now that the banks have added billions of dollars to 
their reserves for such loans 
the bankers were on the defensive following a string of downbeat 
assessments of the industry 
the latest was a report by the general accounting office issued 
tuesday that said the federal deposit insurance corp which 
insures deposits at the nations banks could be wiped out by 
losses banks are suffering from declining real estate values and 
risky investments 
the gao the auditing arm of congress said at least 35 of the 
nations 200 largest banks are likely to fail or require assistance 
over the next year at a cost to the government of 44 billion to 
63 billion the fdic already faces losses of 2 billion this 
year in addition to losses of 51 billion in 1988 and 1989 the 
gao said 
a 13 billion fund balance could be eliminated by the costs 
related to one or more large money center banks with assets of 130 
billion said comptroller general charles a bowsher who directs 
the gao while im not saying that any money center banks are 
currently in danger of failing this demonstrates the vulnerability 
of the fund 
but esposito said he doubted the fdic would run into trouble 
largely because the premiums banks pay into the fund have gone up 
he conceded there are going to be swings and cycles but 
said the abas economists have drawn up projections that show the 
fund will increase over time 
