<TEXT>
the head of the american stock exchange said 
tuesday that he expects the globalization of securities markets in 
the 1990s will lead to a shakeout among smaller exchanges in this 
country 
i would be very suprised to see more than three significant 
marketplaces survive the 1990s amex chairman james r jones told 
the national economists club 
jones a former oklahoma congressman also said he expected only 
one of those three survivors to trade solely through electronic 
methods 
currently the amex and the larger new york stock exchange trade 
through the inperson auction system between buyers and sellers 
the 14 smaller exchanges are linked to the larger new york 
exchanges to facilitate transactions 
i think for most of the regional exchanges theyre going to 
have a very difficult time in the 1990s and i think at the very 
least there will be joint ventures with the larger exchanges 
jones told reporters after giving a talk on the united states role 
in the stock markets of the 1990s 
i dont know how exactly its going to come out he said 
i think its going to be very hard for some of the smaller 
regional exchanges to compete to have the capital needed for new 
technology etc etc so i think youll either see mergers or 
perhaps joint ventures 
just back from meetings of the international stock exchange 
association in frankfurt and berlin jones said the united states 
also will have to liberalize its securities laws 
were going to have to revisit our own securities laws and ask 
if were going to make them so rigid that they would not be 
competitive in the world market he said 
jones also said it would be a mistake to impose a tax on 
securities transactions a revenueraising plan said to be under 
consideration by budget negotiators when other countries are 
lowering or eliminating theirs 
he noted that options trading moved from sweden to london after 
the swedish government imposed a transaction tax 
a transaction tax would make us noncompetitive he said 
