its no secret that the oil futures market loves 
a good rumor but the mill has been working overtime since the iraq 
invasion of kuwait 
somebody on the floor will say we heard this this and that 
and people will start trading pretty quickly said annlouise 
hittle a senior oil analyst with shearson lehman brothers inc 
i think this is a very unusual situation because were in 
an uncertain situation in the middle east 
with most petroleum prices keying off futures the gossip game 
can eventually have an impact far beyond the trading floors these 
days consumers fill their cars with gasoline or stock up on home 
heating oil that costs more money thanks in large measure to what 
happened on the new york mercantile exchange 
sure rumors can ultimately affect the consumer said art 
wiese spokesman for the american petroleum institute gauging the 
impact would be hard however 
youd have to be able to determine fairly specifically what 
the impact of the rumor was versus all the other things going on 
in the market all day wiese said 
executives of the merc view any trading based on rumors as a 
momentary aberration according to neal l wolkoff senior vice 
president for regulatory affairs and operations 
i would think that a market move of an hour would tend to be 
corrected fairly quickly and would have a minimum impact on 
peoples pocket books wolkoff said in an interview tuesday 
but the price paid for current delivery of oil largely reflects 
the price established in the futures market 
speculation on contracts for future delivery of petroleum 
products has virtually eliminated longterm pricing in the 
industry forcing oil buyers to pay a price similar to the latest 
merc price 
the effects of the grapevine were apparent monday when lower 
oil prices were suddenly pushed higher late in the afternoon on 
rumors that iraq had either amassed troops on the jordanian border 
or even sent troops into jordan 
there were also rumors that iraqi paratroopers had attacked 
saudi arabian oilfields or that shooting had broken out in the 
military standoff 
exchange officials said tuesday they were looking into what 
happened to determine whether any rumor was spread with an intent 
to influence prices 
were trying to investigate wolkoff said its obviously 
very difficult to get to the source of a story that gets started 
then somehow gets repeated then somehow gets adopted 
the merc would not hesitate to discipline anyone trying to 
manipulate the market through rumors or even to turn them in to 
the justice department wolkoff said 
as much as merc managers dislike floor rumors they have been 
around since the exchange began trading oil in 1983 
in the 80s there were occasional rumors of the ayatollahs 
death wolkoff said referring to past iranian crises there 
were rumors that the president president reagan died these 
things affected the markets across the board the rumors of the 
ayatollah ruhollah khomeinis death perhaps had more impact than 
his death 
