<DOCNO> AP900911-0285 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
airline passengers bumped from overbooked 
flights can turn down the free tickets and refunds theyre offered 
and sue for damages a federal appeals court ruled tuesday 
in a case from montana a threejudge panel of the 9th us 
circuit court of appeals said a federal ban on direct state 
regulation of airlines does not prevent a passenger from suing 
under ordinary state law for harm caused by airline practices 
the ruling allows william d west a helena mont patent 
lawyer to pursue a suit against northwest airlines for selling 
tickets that cannot be exchanged or refunded but are subject to 
bumping when flights are overbooked west is seeking punitive 
damages 
selling nonrefundable tickets limits a travelers ability to 
make changes but not the airlines ability to switch to a 
smallersize aircraft increasing the chances of bumping said 
attorney cornish hitchcock of the public citizen litigation group 
a ralph nader organization that helped represent west 
the right to sue for overbooking was established in a 1976 
supreme court decision a case that started when allegheny airlines 
bumped nader from a washingtontohartford flight in tuesdays 
ruling the appeals court said the federal deregulation of airlines 
in 1978 did not prohibit all such suits 
the airline was studying the ruling tuesday and had no comment 
said its lawyer jon metropoulos 
hitchcock said wests case was unusual because it holds the 
possibility of sizable damages if the airline is found to have 
acted in bad faith under montana law 
many airlines offer freetrip coupons to passengers on 
overbooked flights federal law also entitles a bumped passenger to 
a refund of the ticket price up to 200 if a substitute flight is 
more than an hour later than the original flight or twice those 
amounts if more than two hours late hitchcock said the typical 
traveler probably should take one of those options rather than sue 
we generally recommend that people take the money or take the 
free ticket as a quick and easy way of resolving the matter he 
said the litigation can drag on for some time and theres no 
guarantee of recovery 
west was bumped from a northwest flight from great falls mont 
to arlington va in september 1986 when the airline switched from 
a 146passenger plane to a 78passenger plane without warning 
ticket agents west who had been scheduled to land in arlington at 
9 pm turned down an alternative flight to a nearby airport at 3 
am and instead rescheduled his trip two weeks later 
his suit under montana law for badfaith dealing by the airline 
was dismissed by us district judge charles lovell which said it 
was barred by federal law but the appeals court disagreed 
the 1978 federal airline deregulation law which prohibited 
state laws relating to rates routes or services of any air 
carrier bars only those state laws that purport to regulate 
airlines said judge dorothy nelson in the 30 ruling 
state laws that merely have an effect on airline services are 
not preempted nelson said she said one such law was the 
montana statute invoked by west requiring goodfaith conduct 
between buyers and sellers or any other parties in a contract 
the court said it was not deciding whether west had a valid 
claim under that law only that he had a right to sue 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

