opening arguments began in the trial of 14 currency traders accused 
of cheating customers 
attorneys ed genson and joseph duffy the first to make their 
opening statements before us district judge william t hart 
imitated the rapid calls and hand signals of the pit they 
described the noise and stress caused by about 100 traders 
competing for currency futures contracts every business day 
they also questioned the worth as evidence of surreptitious 
tapes made by undercover fbi agent dieter volk who posed as a 
corrupt trader as part of a sting investigation at the worlds two 
largest futures exchanges 
the pit is not a quiet whispery place said genson 
attorney for independent yen trader robert bailin 36 
his comment was a challenge to the opening statement of 
assistant us attorney lisa huestes 
you will be hearing about whispered conversation after 
whispered conversation huestes told the jurors earlier tuesday 
huestes said the government would try to show systematic 
collusion between brokers and independent or local yen 
traders to defraud the brokers customers often through locals 
agreeing to buy brokers erroneous contracts in exchange for 
trading favors she said the motivation was plain and simple 
greed 
duffy defense attorney for john m baker 51 said many of the 
tapes volk made of baker were made in a bar where volk often 
bought beers for the broker 
the fbi recorded the musings of a drunk thats not credible 
evidence he said 
the charges resulted from an unprecedented undercover 
investigation in which fbi agents posed as corrupt traders they 
secretly taperecorded conversations among traders at the two 
commodity exchanges 
a federal grand jury indicted 48 people in the probe twenty 
have pleaded guilty and one pleaded no contest 
in the first trial resulting from the investigation a us 
district court jury in july convicted two swiss franc traders of 
relatively minor trading violations and acquitted a third 
the jury could not reach verdicts on scores of more serious 
charges including a racketeering count against one of the three 
defendants the men are to be tried again on those charges early 
next year 
</TEXT>
